Linear Regression:

Overview

    Comes Under Supervised Machine Learning.
    Linear means Straight line.
    The model finds the best fit linear line between the independent and dependent variable i.e it finds the linear relationship between the dependent and independent variable.
    In statistics, linear regression is a statistical model which estimates the linear relationship between a scalar response and one or more explanatory variables (also known as dependent and independent variables). The case of one explanatory variable is called simple linear regression; for more than one, the process is called multiple linear regression.
    It is used for predictive analysis. It makes predictions for continuous/real or numeric variables such as sales, salary, age, product price, etc.

Dataset for Linear Regression:

    Linearity

Linearity:

    * Linearity can be checked using scatter plot and Pearson coefficient for all the independent variables vs target variable. Same results can be achieved by pairplot and Pearson coefficient using corr_matrix.
    * If all the independent variables are linear to target variable, then the model will perform better.
    * If some of the variables are non linear, then we have to transform the variables. Even after transformation, not linear to target variable, then we can remove that variable.

Types:

  Simple Linear Regression
  Multiple Linear Regression

Simple Linear Regression

  In simple linear regression, the model assumes a linear relationship between the dependent variable and a single independent variable. The algorithm finds the best-fit line that represents the relationship between the two variables by minimizing the sum of the squared errors between the predicted and actual values.   

  The equation for a simple linear regression model with one independent variable can be written as:
        y = b0 + b1x
  Where:
  y is the dependent variable
  x is the independent variable
  b0 is the intercept (the point where the line intersects the y-axis)
  b1 is the slope of the line (the change in y for each unit change in x)

Multiple Linear Regression

  In multiple linear regression, the model assumes a linear relationship between the dependent variable and multiple independent variables. The algorithm finds the best-fit plane or hyperplane that represents the relationship between the variables by minimizing the sum of the squared errors.

        y = b0 + b1x1 + b2x2 + ... + bnxn
  Where:
  y is the dependent variable
  x1, x2, ..., xn are the independent variables
  b0 is the intercept
  b1, b2, ..., bn are the coefficients of the independent variables

What is the best Fit Line?

    Our primary objective while using linear regression is to locate the best-fit line, which implies that the error between the predicted and actual values should be kept to a minimum. There will be the least error in the best-fit line.

Cost Function for Linear Regression

The cost function or the loss function is nothing but the error or difference between the predicted value ^ and the true value Y.

In Linear Regression, the Mean Squared Error (MSE) cost function is employed, which calculates the average of the squared errors between the predicted values and the actual values . The purpose is to determine the optimal values for the intercept 1 and the coefficient of the input feature 2 providing the best-fit line for the given data points. The linear equation expressing this relationship is ^ =1 + 2.

MSE function can be calculated as:

Cost function(J) = n=1  n=i (y^i yi)2

Utilizing the MSE function, the iterative process of gradient descent is applied to update the values of 1 & 2. This ensures that the MSE value converges to the global minima, signifying the most accurate fit of the linear regression line to the dataset.

# Define the target variable
target = 'MedHouseVal'

# Plot scatter plots for each feature against the target variable
for column in df.columns[:-1]:
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.scatterplot(x=df[column], y=df[target])
    plt.title(f'Scatter plot of {column} vs {target}')
    plt.xlabel(column)
    plt.ylabel(target)
    plt.show()

    # Calculate and display the Pearson correlation coefficient
    corr, _ = pearsonr(df[column], df[target])
    print(f'Pearson correlation coefficient between {column} and {target}: {corr:.2f}')

In[6]:
# Split the data
X = df.drop('MedHouseVal', axis=1)
y = df['MedHouseVal']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Fit the model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Plot residuals
residuals = y_test - y_pred
plt.scatter(y_pred, residuals)
plt.xlabel('Fitted values')
plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.title('Residuals vs. Fitted values')
plt.show()
In[7]:
# Durbin-Watson test
# Add a constant to the model
X_train_const = sm.add_constant(X_train)
model_sm = sm.OLS(y_train, X_train_const).fit()
print('Durbin-Watson statistic:', sm.stats.durbin_watson(model_sm.resid))

Durbin-Watson statistic: 1.9641152439594485
In[8]:
# Q-Q plot
sm.qqplot(model_sm.resid, line ='45')
plt.show()

# Shapiro-Wilk test
shapiro_test = stats.shapiro(model_sm.resid)
print('Shapiro-Wilk test:', shapiro_test)
